Critical Windows Findings
P0. Runtime Contract Split Breaks Product Features
Windows starts the engine directly through FFI in platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/Program.cs:182. The FFI layer then creates a Windows named-pipe handler in deskdrop-core/src/ffi.rs:78, but that handler only supports a subset of IPC and returns "unsupported in FFI IPC" for the rest at deskdrop-core/src/ffi.rs:181.
The Windows UI expects daemon-style status fields:
peer_batteries in platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/DeskdropStore.cs:127
active_transfers in platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/DeskdropStore.cs:154
active_call in platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/DeskdropStore.cs:168
But the embedded FFI status handler only returns peers, peer count, local fingerprint, bind IP, and bind port. This makes large parts of the Windows UI aspirational rather than real.
Recommendation: choose one runtime model.
Preferred: Windows app owns or launches the Rust daemon and talks to the full daemon IPC protocol.
Acceptable short term: make the FFI Windows pipe handler reuse the exact same dispatcher as deskdrop-core/src/bin/daemon.rs and deskdrop-core/src/ipc.rs.
Do not keep two divergent protocol implementations.
P0. Action Feedback Is Often Invisible
MainWindow.ShowToast is effectively commented out in platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/MainWindow.xaml.cs:309, but many dashboard actions call it: settings saved, QR command, manual connect, send files, camera errors, context menu install, and drag/drop send. This creates silent or invisible success/failure states.
Some paths use NotificationHelper.ShowToast, but the UI-level toast layer is not unified. A premium Windows app needs one notification/feedback service that supports inline toast, Action Center notifications, retry actions, and error details.
P0. Pairing And Trust Are Not Product-Ready
Windows has QR pairing UI, but the implementation is inconsistent:
Command palette "Show Magic Link (QR)" creates QRCodeWindow(GetLocalIPAddress(), "000000") at platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/MainWindow.xaml.cs:217, which is not the Android deskdrop://pair?... format and displays a fake PIN.
QRPairingWindow reads device_name, fingerprint_display, bind_ip, and bind_port from the response root, but IPC responses wrap fields inside data. As a result it falls back to local/default values even when richer daemon data exists.
ShowTofuPrompt at platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/MainWindow.xaml.cs:749 stores state but the visible prompt fields and overlay are commented out.
Trust/reject handlers exist at platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/MainWindow.xaml.cs:760, but the actual user-facing trust dialog is missing.
In platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/Program.cs:565, TOFU uses id = name because the precompiled DLL lacks deskdrop_event_device_id; this is unsafe because names are not stable device IDs.
Windows cannot be considered seamless until pairing is a complete guided flow with fingerprint/PIN verification, retry states, and clear success/failure.
P0. Transfers UI Is Not Actually Wired To Transfer Controls
The Windows transfer template binds to ActionIcon1, ActionColor1, ActionCommand1, ActionIcon2, and ActionCommand2 at platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/MainWindow.xaml:312, but FileTransferState does not define those members. WPF will fail those bindings silently.
The Windows FFI event layer auto-accepts incoming transfers in platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/Program.cs:529, but there is no product decision or user policy shown in the UI. Also:
No progress event accessor is exposed in Windows FFI.
Pause/resume/cancel are not wired from UI to IPC.
Incoming accept/reject is not surfaced.
Completed transfer history click is a placeholder at platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/MainWindow.xaml.cs:904.
File sending uses File.ReadAllBytes in platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/Program.cs:369 and platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/Program.cs:413, which is not acceptable for large files.
Target behavior should mirror macOS and Android: progress, speed, ETA, accept/reject, pause/resume/cancel, cancel from notification, and reveal in Explorer.
P0. History And Activity Have Two Sources Of Truth
Windows keeps in-memory history in ClipboardManager, mirrors some items into DeskdropStore.Shared.History, and also has a core/daemon history API available through IPC. The UI is not consistently backed by the durable core history.
Problems:
Quick access pin/delete mutates DeskdropStore.Shared.History directly instead of using ClipboardManager.DeleteHistory or core history APIs.
HistoryItem.IsPinned does not implement property change notification, so pin color/order can be stale.
Pinning does not resort the list.
The dashboard transfer history is populated only when LoadTransfersView runs.
The macOS-style activity feed features in the core are not exposed on Windows.
Recommendation: Windows should use the same activity/history contract as macOS: activity_recent, activity_since, pending_remote_clipboards, apply_clipboard, history_pin, history_delete, history_search, and history_repush.
P1. Windows Visual Style Is Polished-Looking But Not Native Enough
The WPF shell uses comments and tokens labeled as macOS in platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/MainWindow.xaml. The bottom floating capsule and traffic-light heritage are visually borrowed from macOS. The result is attractive but not convincingly Windows-native.
Windows should adopt Fluent 2 conventions:
Mica or Acrylic host backdrop, not transparent WPF window plus hand-made card shell.
Segoe UI Variable and Windows 11 spacing/focus.
NavigationView-like structure or a compact left rail for larger dashboards.
Native caption buttons and snap layout support.
Dark mode and high contrast from system settings.
Windows App SDK notifications where possible.
Fluent symbols or Segoe Fluent Icons with consistent sizing.
P1. Settings Are Far Behind macOS And Android
Windows settings currently expose device name, launch at login, sync enabled, and notifications. Several controls are commented out in platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/MainWindow.xaml.cs:548 to platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/MainWindow.xaml.cs:617.
Missing or incomplete:
Sync mode: auto/manual/receive-only.
Content types: text/images/files.
Timeline-first/auto-apply policy.
Max payload, history limit, max stored text size.
Clipboard polling, debounce, duplicate window, rate limits.
Sensitive text blocking and ignore patterns.
Require TOFU confirmation.
Local fingerprint display.
Per-peer settings.
Theme/dark mode.
Shortcut customization.
Dirty state, validation, save result, and revert.
The macOS settings model is the target.
P1. Diagnostics Are Too Shallow
Windows diagnostics only checks daemon running/stopped and offers app restart. It should become a real repair surface:
Daemon/app host running.
IPC pipe reachable.
mDNS/discovery state.
Bound port and conflicts.
Windows Firewall rule.
Network profile: private/public/domain.
Clipboard watcher status.
Notification permission/AUMID status.
Startup task status.
Trusted device count and recent reconnect failures.
Latest crash log.
Export support bundle.
P1. Camera And Call Continuity Are Inconsistent
Camera preview polls latest_camera_frame in platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/CameraPreviewWindow.xaml.cs:31, but daemon responses contain data.frame_base64 in deskdrop-core/src/bin/daemon.rs:779; the Windows preview expects data itself to be a string. In the embedded FFI IPC model, latest_camera_frame is unsupported anyway.
Incoming call exists in two forms: an inline dashboard banner and IncomingCallBannerWindow. Actions use "reject" in one place and "decline" in another. Android has real call action fallback through notification listener and TelecomManager; Windows should show a consistent continuity panel and send one canonical action vocabulary.
P1. Hotkeys Are Useful But Not User-Configurable
Windows registers several global shortcuts in platforms/windows/Deskdrop.Windows/Program.cs:791 onward:
Ctrl+Shift+V for quick access.
Ctrl+K for dashboard command palette.
Ctrl+Shift+L for active browser URL.
Ctrl+Shift+D for drop zone.
Ctrl+Shift+C for push clipboard.
These are powerful, but there is no conflict UI, no settings page, and no visible onboarding. A global Ctrl+K is especially likely to conflict with applications. Shortcuts should be customizable and disabled if registration fails.
P1. Explorer Integration Needs A Windows-Grade Design
The context menu installer writes to HKEY_CLASSES_ROOT\*\shell\Deskdrop and asks for Administrator if it fails. A polished app should avoid admin where possible:
Use per-user registration under HKCU.
Add uninstall/repair state in settings.
Support "Send with Deskdrop" target selection.
Support folders and multi-select.
Consider Windows Share target/protocol registration.
P2. Notification System Is Basic
NotificationHelper uses WinRT toast templates with ToastNotificationManager.CreateToastNotifier("Deskdrop"). Without robust app identity/start-menu shortcut/AUMID handling, notifications can be unreliable. They also lack action buttons.
Target:
Receive clipboard: Apply, Copy, Open Quick Access.
File incoming: Accept, Reject.
Transfer complete: Show in Explorer.
Pairing request: Trust, Reject, View fingerprint.
Call: Accept, Decline.
Failure: Retry, Open Diagnostics.
P2. Accessibility, Localization, And Scaling Are Not Yet Designed
WPF UI mostly lacks automation names, focus states, keyboard traversal contracts, screen reader labels, high contrast behavior, reduced motion behavior, localization, and text expansion handling. This matters because a Windows desktop app will be used at many DPI scales, display densities, and accessibility modes.
