Proposed Windows Product Architecture
1. Unify The Engine Contract
Create a single Windows-facing engine gateway:
EngineClient: typed async IPC client with request/response models.
EngineHost: starts/stops daemon or embedded core, but exposes the same protocol either way.
EngineEventStream: pushes events to UI instead of relying only on one-second polling.
EngineStateStore: one source of truth for peers, activity, transfers, settings, diagnostics, call state, battery, and toasts.
The Windows UI should not know whether the engine is daemon-backed or embedded. It should only know typed state and commands.
2. Prefer Daemon IPC For Windows
The macOS architecture already benefits from a rich IPC daemon. Windows should move toward the same model:
App starts hidden tray/dashboard.
App ensures daemon is running.
App talks to \\.\pipe\deskdrop.
Daemon owns mDNS, core state, file transfer lifecycle, history, settings, and event stream.
This avoids divergent FFI behavior and lets Windows reuse the same protocol surface as macOS and CLI.
3. Make UI State Durable And Observable
Replace ad hoc in-memory state with durable models:
PeerViewModel
ActivityEntryViewModel
TransferViewModel
SettingsSnapshot
DiagnosticsSnapshot
TrustPromptViewModel
ToastViewModel
CommandDescriptor
Collections should update by diffing IDs, not clear/re-add every second. This prevents flicker, preserves selection, and makes the UI feel alive rather than polling-bound.
4. Split The Monolith
Program.cs and MainWindow.xaml are too large for a premium app. Split:
NativeCore.cs or remove if daemon IPC wins.
ClipboardManager.cs
TrayApp.cs
AppEntry.cs
EngineClient.cs
EngineStore.cs
