Proposed UX Redesign
First Run Onboarding
Windows needs a first-run journey as strong as Android:
Welcome: "Deskdrop keeps clipboard and files on your local network."
Network readiness: show current network, private/public profile, firewall status, port.
Pair device: show QR code and manual IP; optionally scan QR with webcam.
Trust verification: show device name, platform, SAS PIN, fingerprint, and explicit Trust/Reject.
Send sample: send "Hello from Windows" to selected device and confirm receipt.
Finish: enable launch at login, open Quick Access, show shortcuts.
Dashboard Shell
Use a Windows-native layout:
Top app bar with app title, status pill, search/command entry, scan button, send button, settings.
Left rail or compact tab bar: Home, Activity, Devices, Transfers, Settings, Diagnostics.
Main content should not be trapped inside nested cards.
Bottom floating macOS dock should be removed or redesigned as a Windows navigation rail.
Home
Purpose: answer "is Deskdrop working and what can I do now?"
Must include:
Connection status and last sync.
Current clipboard preview with "Send to all" and target dropdown.
Active transfer summary.
Nearby/paired devices summary.
Latest activity.
Important repair prompts if daemon/firewall/network is unhealthy.
Devices
Purpose: manage trust and targets.
Device card states:
Nearby untrusted: Pair, Ignore.
Pairing requested: Show PIN/fingerprint, Trust, Reject.
Trusted connected: Send clipboard, Send files, Disconnect, Pause sync, Rename, Details.
Trusted offline: Connect, Forget, Auto-connect toggle.
Device detail drawer: fingerprint, first seen, last seen, IP, platform, battery, settings.
Activity
Purpose: timeline-first clipboard and system history.
Features:
Search.
Filters: All, Clipboard, Files, Devices, Warnings.
Day grouping.
Pending clipboard banner with Apply Latest.
Row actions: Apply, Copy, Send Again, Pin, Delete, Show in Explorer.
Expanded preview for text.
Empty states that tell the next useful action.
Transfers
Purpose: confident file movement.
Active transfer row:
File icon, name, source/target, status.
Progress, speed, ETA, transferred bytes.
Incoming: Accept, Reject, Save As if supported.
Active: Pause, Cancel.
Paused: Resume, Cancel.
Complete: Show in Explorer, Send Again.
Failed: Retry, Details.
Quick Access
Purpose: fast clipboard memory.
Keep it small but powerful:
Search field.
Current clipboard quick send.
Recent activity rows.
Pending clipboard apply.
Pin/delete/send actions.
Keyboard navigation.
Open dashboard button.
Correct screen positioning across multi-monitor setups.
Command Palette
Purpose: power-user flow.
Match macOS depth:
Grouped commands: Navigate, Clipboard, Devices, Transfers, Network, Settings.
Dynamic commands per connected device.
Search history entries when query is typed.
Disabled states with reason.
Shortcut hints.
Recent commands.
Settings
Suggested Windows settings sections:
General: device name, launch at login, theme, onboarding replay.
Sync: enable sync, sync mode, text/images/files, timeline-first, auto-apply.
Network: port, manual connect defaults, discovery, firewall repair.
Security: require TOFU, local fingerprint, block likely secrets, ignore patterns.
History: history limit, max text size, clear/export.
Notifications: receive banners, action center behavior, mirrored Android notifications.
Shortcuts: hotkey enable/customize/conflict status.
Integrations: Explorer context menu, protocol handler, jump lists.
Advanced: rate limits, debounce, duplicate window, logs.
Diagnostics
Diagnostics should become a repair console:
App host: running, version, uptime.
IPC: named pipe reachable, latency.
Engine: running, device ID, fingerprint.
Network: current adapter, IP, network profile, mDNS status.
Port: bound, conflict detection.
Firewall: rule present and enabled.
Clipboard: watcher active, last sequence number.
Notifications: app identity/AUMID, permission, last toast result.
Startup: launch at login status.
Transfers: active count, stuck transfer detector.
Logs: open log folder, copy diagnostics, export zip.
Implementation Roadmap
Phase 0: Stabilize The Contract
Goal: make the existing app honest and shippable before visual polish.
Decide daemon IPC vs embedded FFI.
If embedded remains, route Windows FFI IPC through the full IpcRequest dispatcher.
Fix latest_camera_frame response parsing.
Fix QRPairingWindow response unwrapping and standard URI.
Restore visible toast/inline feedback.
Add a visible TOFU trust prompt.
Replace transfer action placeholder bindings with real commands or remove the buttons until wired.
Stop reading entire large files into memory; use file-path transfer where possible.
Add typed response error handling in WindowsIpcClient.
Add a Windows CI build check and make it blocking.
Phase 1: Match Core Product Parity
Goal: Windows reaches the baseline of macOS/Android features.
Implement durable activity feed from core IPC.
Implement pending clipboard apply/copy/resend.
Implement transfer controls: incoming accept/reject, pause/resume/cancel, retry, reveal.
Implement full devices management: trust, reject, rename, forget, pause/resume sync, auto-connect.
Implement full settings panes and save through save_settings.
Implement real diagnostics.
Add first-run onboarding.
Phase 2: Fluent Windows Polish
Goal: Windows feels like a premium Windows app, not a port.
Build FluentTokens.xaml with light/dark/high-contrast tokens.
Replace macOS-like floating dock with Windows-native navigation.
Use Mica/Acrylic appropriately.
Adopt Segoe UI Variable and consistent icon sizing.
Add system theme detection.
Add focus visuals, keyboard navigation, screen reader names.
Add reduce-motion support.
Improve tray icon assets for light/dark/high DPI.
Replace UI emoji with Fluent icons.
Phase 3: Seamlessness And OS Integrations
Goal: make Windows feel ambient and reliable.
Network/sleep resume hooks with immediate reconnect.
Firewall repair flow.
Actionable notifications.
Per-user Explorer context menu with uninstall/repair.
Protocol handler for deskdrop://.
Optional Share target if packaging supports it.
Jump list actions with status-sensitive commands.
Hotkey settings and conflict reporting.
Multi-monitor quick access/drop-zone positioning.
Phase 4: QA, Release, And Support
Goal: confidence.
Automated build: Windows WPF/WinUI, Rust core, installer.
Smoke tests for IPC commands.
UI automation for onboarding, pairing prompt, settings save, command palette.
Manual test matrix: Windows 10, Windows 11, light/dark, high DPI, high contrast, sleep/resume, public/private network, firewall on/off.
Transfer tests: tiny file, 100 MB, folder/multi-file, cancel, pause/resume, disconnect/reconnect.
Pairing tests: Android -> Windows, Windows -> Android, macOS -> Windows, Windows -> macOS.
Diagnostics export sanity check.
